{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"body":"FIELD FINDING — REFINEMENT (supersedes the 'non-convergent gate' framing in the prior comment). After the operator directed a root-cause pass, the evidence substantially revises that conclusion:\n\n1. The novelty rising floor + remediation_mode ARE active on origin/main (remediation_mode=True, novelty_drop_active=True defaults; re-reviews emitted REVIEW_RESULT sidecars and dropped 1/3/9 low-priority novel findings). It targets low-priority (<0.4) advisory churn and correctly does NOT floor high-impact (0.85-1.0) blocking findings — so it is not, and should not be, the lever for blocking convergence.\n\n2. The blocking findings were VALID and code-accurate — the gate's precision was high throughout. What looked like 'non-convergence / verdict oscillation' was mostly MY remediations introducing NEW factual inaccuracies each round, which the gate correctly caught: I invented a non-existent eval field (scorer_args), misidentified a DET detector (there is no P6 sibling-overlap detector; P5 already emits subjects), over-engineered new context-plumbing for G7 when the ticket's intent was to read the parent via the always-available show_ticket tool, and mislabeled G7 CODEBASE_GROUNDED when tooling is granted by agentic execution_mode. EVERY leaf converged to PASS the moment its plan was corrected AGAINST THE ACTUAL SOURCE rather than against my assumptions — a8e5, 74d9, 9f25, b9c0 all passed on the code-grounded revision.\n\n3. Genuine residual frictions (smaller than first claimed, still real for the measurement note): (a) verdict INSTABILITY at the margin (74d9/a8e5 flipped INDETERMINATE<->BLOCK on unchanged plans once each) — real but not the dominant effect; (b) NEW-CODE grounding INDETERMINATE for plans referencing not-yet-written code; (c) exhaustive test-blast-radius enumerated one pinning test per round rather than all at once.\n\nREVISED TAKEAWAY for calibration: the plan-review claim gate is high-precision and effectively convergent WHEN the plan is made factually accurate against the codebase; the expensive rounds here were driven by plan inaccuracy (agent-side), not gate over-tightness. The mirror of the code-review looseness this epic fixes is NOT plan-review over-tightness — it is plan-review's correct insistence on code-accurate plans, which is costly for large new-code plans but not wrong. 10/11 tickets earned a genuine signed PASS with no --force."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1783901324326374001,"uuid":"f5d47cf1-c44e-446c-a612-3a5dc406a5fe"}